#: ../../../commercial/sharing.rst:41
msgid "Secret link"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../commercial/sharing.rst:43
msgid ""
"Once the person you send the link to clicks it, they will have access to the "
"documentation while their browser window is open."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../commercial/sharing.rst:46
msgid ""
"If you want to link to a specific page, you can do this by passing the "
"``next`` query parameter in the URL. For example ``https://mydocs."
"readthedocs-hosted.com/_/sharing/xxxxxxxxx?next=/en/latest/page.html``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../commercial/sharing.rst:51
msgid ""
"This is useful for sharing access to an entire set of documentation for a "
"user. You can embed these links in an internal wiki, for example, and all "
"your employees will be able to browse the docs without a login."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../commercial/sharing.rst:56
msgid "Password"
msgstr "密碼"

#: ../../../commercial/sharing.rst:58
msgid ""
"Once the person you send the link to clicks on the link, they will see an "
"*Authorization required* page asking them for the password you generated. "
"When the user enters the password, they will gain access to view your "
"project."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../commercial/sharing.rst:64
msgid ""
"This is useful for when you have documentation you want users to bookmark. "
"They can enter a URL directly and enter the password when prompted."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../commercial/sharing.rst:68
msgid "HTTP Authorization Header"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../commercial/sharing.rst:71
msgid ""
"This approach is useful for automated scripts. It only allows access to a "
"page when the header is present, so it doesn't allow browsing docs inside of "
"a browser."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../commercial/sharing.rst:76
msgid "Token Authorization"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../commercial/sharing.rst:78
msgid ""
"You need to send the ``Authorization`` header with the token on each HTTP "
"request. The header has the form ``Authorization: Token <TOKEN>``. For "
"example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../commercial/sharing.rst:85
msgid ""
"curl -H \"Authorization: Token $TOKEN\" https://docs.example.com/en/latest/"
"example.html"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../commercial/sharing.rst:87
msgid "Basic Authorization"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../commercial/sharing.rst:89
msgid ""
"You can also use basic authorization, with the token as user and an empty "
"password. For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../commercial/sharing.rst:95
msgid ""
"curl --url https://docs.example.com/en/latest/example.html --user '$TOKEN:'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../commercial/sharing.rst:97
msgid "Typical sharing configurations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../commercial/sharing.rst:99
msgid ""
"There are a few common ways to architect sharing, with trade-offs between "
"them, and you should choose the one that best fits your use case."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../commercial/sharing.rst:104
msgid "Bulk passwords"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../commercial/sharing.rst:106
msgid ""
"If you want to limit access to a group of users, you can create a password "
"for each user, and then share the password with them. This allows users to "
"access the documentation directly, but requires more management on your end. "
"Any time a new user needs access or you want to remove access, you will need "
"to generate a new password for them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../commercial/sharing.rst:115
msgid "Authenticated redirect"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../commercial/sharing.rst:117
msgid ""
"If you want to share documentation with a group of users, you need to "
"authenticate those users against your own system first. The simplest way to "
"do this is to create an authenticated redirect on your site, which then "
"redirects to the Read the Docs :ref:`commercial/sharing:secret link`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../commercial/sharing.rst:122
msgid ""
"This should require very little customization, and will ensure that only "
"authenticated users can access the documentation. The downside is that users "
"won't be able to access the documentation directly from a bookmark, and will "
"have to go through your site first."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../commercial/sharing.rst:128
msgid "Authenticated proxy"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../commercial/sharing.rst:130
msgid ""
"If you want a more transparent experience for your users, you can create a "
"proxy that authenticates users against your system, and then proxies the "
"request to Read the Docs. This is more complex to set up, but will allow "
"users to access the documentation directly from a bookmark."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../commercial/sharing.rst:136
msgid ""
"This approach would use a :ref:`commercial/sharing:HTTP Authorization "
"Header` to authenticate users, and would be configured in your proxy server."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../commercial/sharing.rst:140
msgid "Proxy example"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../commercial/sharing.rst:142
msgid ""
"Below is an example of how to configure Nginx to proxy requests to Read the "
"Docs while adding the token in the `Authorization` header."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../commercial/sharing.rst:144
msgid ""
"server {\n"
"    listen 80;\n"
"    server_name docs.example.com;\n"
"\n"
"    location / {\n"
"        proxy_pass https://docs-example.readthedocs-hosted.com;\n"
"\n"
"        # Add Authorization header with the token\n"
"        proxy_set_header Authorization \"Token <TOKEN>\";\n"
"\n"
"        # Optionally forward other headers\n"
"        proxy_set_header Host $host;\n"
"        proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;\n"
"        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;\n"
"        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-Proto $scheme;\n"
"    }\n"
"}"
msgstr ""
